03995nam a22006255i 9780674273450DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222004mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806742734507 a10.4159/97806742734502doi  a(DE-B1597)613893  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aML410.H13 7aMUS0060002bisacsh04a782.48092  aLP 39136qHBZ2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/106562:1 aHarris, Ellen T., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHandel as Orpheus :bVoice and Desire in the Chamber Cantatas /cEllen T. Harris. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2022] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (448 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on the Musical Examples -- tPrologue: “The Ways of the World” -- t1. Code Names and Assumed Identities -- t2. Women’s Voices/Men’s Voices -- t3. Pastoral Lovers -- t4. Cantata Couples and Love Triangles -- t5. Silence and Secrecy -- t6. Culmination of the Private -- tEpilogue: “True Representation” -- tAppendix 1: Cantata Chronology -- tAppendix 2: Texts and Translations of the Continuo Cantatas -- tBibliographic Abbreviations -- tNotes -- tTitle Index of Handel’s Cantatas, Duets, and Trios -- tGeneral Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHandel wrote over 100 cantatas, compositions for voice and instruments that describe the joy and pain of love. In Handel as Orpheus, the first comprehensive study of the cantatas, Ellen Harris investigates their place in Handel's life as well as their extraordinary beauty. The cantatas were written between 1706 and 1723--from the time Handel left his home in Germany, through the years he spent in Florence and Rome, and into the early part of his London career. In this period he lived as a guest in aristocratic homes, and composed these chamber works for his patrons and hosts, primarily for private entertainments. In both Italy and England his patrons moved in circles in which same-sex desire was commonplace--a fact that is not without significance, Harris reveals, for the cantatas exhibit a clear homosexual subtext. Addressing questions about style and form, dating, the relation of music to text, rhythmic and tonal devices, and voicing, Handel as Orpheus is an invaluable resource for the study and enjoyment of the cantatas, which have too long been neglected. This innovative study brings greater understanding of Handel, especially his development as a composer, and new insight into the role of sexuality in artistic expression.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aCantatasxHistory and criticism. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Classical.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674273450zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674273450423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674273450/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK